Made of turf; covered with turf.
A lying in concealment; hiding. [Obs.]
Moist. [Obs.]
Pertaining to, or evincing, orthodoxy; orthodox.
The formation of starch.
Furnished with pilasters.
The act of thinking; thought; meditation; contemplation. "Fixedin cogitation deep." Milton.

A red star of the first magnitude, situated in the eye ofTaurus; the Bull's Eye. It is the bright star in the group called theHyades.Now when Aldebaran was mounted high Above the shiny Cassiopeia'schair. Spenser.
One of a race inhabiting the valleys of the Pyrenees, who until1793 were political and social outcasts (Christian Pariahs). They aresupposed to be a remnant of the Visigoths.
Bearing a tuft of soft hairs or down, as the seeds of milkweed.Gray.
To interpose a demurrer. See Demurrer, 2.
A man who sells milk or delivers is to customers.
A young small steer.

The standard atmospheric pressure used in certain physicalmeasurements calculations; conventionally, that pressure under whichthe barometer stands at 760 millimeters, at a temperature of 0Centigrade, at the level of the sea, and in the latitude of Paris.Sir W. Thomson.

An instrument for boring holes, turned by a handle.Specifically:(a) A gimlet. " It is but like the little wimble, to let in thegreater auger." Selden.(b) A stonecutter's brace for boring holes in stone.(c) An auger used for boring in earth.
The quality of being direct; straightness; straightforwardness;immediateness.
Work done at a desk, as by a clerk or writer. Tennyson.
To remove the paint from; to efface, as a painting. Parnell.
Sophistical.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the nutmeg (Myristica).Specifically, designating an acid found in nutmeg oil and otoba fat,and extracted as a white crystalline waxy substance.
Having a large admixture of small pebbles or gravel; -- said ofa soil. Gardner.
Burdensome; troublesome. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The leatherback.
The myristate of glycerin, -- found as a vegetable fat innutmeg butter, etc.

To raise little bladders or blisters upon; to inflame andseparate the cuticle of; to blister. Wiseman.

That part of a fungus which is covered with the hymenium.
